{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}} {{Icelandic name|Arnór}} '''Arnór Hannibalsson''' (1934&ndash;2012) was an Icelandic philosopher, historian, and translator and former professor of philosophy at the [[University of Iceland]]. He completed a master's degree in philosophy at the [[University of Moscow]] and a doctorate in philosophy at the [[University of Edinburgh]] in Scotland.
He was predominantly concerned with aesthetics, philosophy, history, [[epistemology]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.uni-corvinus.hu/gt/1998_1-2_en/2-04.htm |title=SOCIETY AND ECONOMY:EPISTEMOLOGY AND PRACTICE |publisher=Corvinus |accessdate=16 July 2012 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and science. In 1975 he translated [[Roman Ingarden]]'s ''On the Motives which led Husserl to Transcendental Idealism'' from Polish.<ref name="Loscerbo1981">{{cite book|last=Loscerbo|first=John|title=Being and Technology: A Study in the Philosophy of Martin Heidegger|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fWspXHZoABcC&pg=PA285|accessdate=16 July 2012|date=31 July 1981|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-90-247-2411-6|page=285}}</ref> He also contributed to journals with articles such as "Icelandic Historical Science in the Postwar Period, 1944-1957".<ref name="(U.S.)Societies1958">{{cite book|title=Current digest of the Soviet press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cyUJAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=16 July 2012|year=1958|publisher=American Association for the Advancement of Slavic Studies}}</ref>
Arnór had strong anti-Communist views and was said to have been "extremely critical of the Icelandic Socialists" in his 1999/2000 book ''Moskvulínan: Kommúnistaflokkur Íslands og Komintern, Halldór Laxness og Sovétríkin''.<ref name="Olesen2004">{{cite book|last=Olesen|first=Thorsten B.|title=The Cold War and the Nordic countries: historiography at a crossroads|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pClnAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=16 July 2012|year=2004|publisher=University Press of Southern Denmark|isbn=978-87-7838-857-5|page=91}}</ref>
He was the son of [[Hannibal Valdimarsson]], a former minister, and had several sons and one daughter, [[Thora Arnorsdottir]].
He died on December 28, 2012.<ref>http://www.15min.lt/en/article/world/iceland-s-former-foreign-minister-and-lithuania-s-honorary-consul-arnor-hannibalsson-passes-away-529-292990</ref>
==Main publications== * 1978 ''Rökfræðileg aðferðafræði'' (Logical Methodology) * 1979 ''Siðfræði vísinda'' (Ethics of Science) * 1985 ''Heimspeki félagsvísinda'' (Philosophy of Society) * 1985 ''Um rætur þekkingar'' (The Roots of Knowledge) * 1987 ''Fagurfræði'' (Aesthetics) * 1987 ''Söguspeki'' (History Wisdom) * 1999 ''Moskvulínan: Kommúnistaflokkur Íslands og Komintern, Halldór Laxness og Sovétríkin'' (Moscow Line: The [[Communist Party of Iceland]] and the Comintern, [[Halldór Laxness]] and the Soviet Union)
